\section*{Conclusions}


\begin{itemize}
\item After running the 10 days interval data, the p-value is $9.03*10^{-11}$ and the $R^2$ is around 0.27. It indicates that there is an moderate correlation between emotional factors and stock market price from the perspective of this research. However, it may just be the coincidence of the data set. There are still a few improvements of the research. 
\item How we actually calculate the emotion is flawed. Think more about the content of the scoring mechanism, people will naturally realize that our emotions do not purely depend on the word we choose, but also include the content of the sentences. 
\item The keywords search should be more generalized
\item Tweets capturing accuracy
\end{itemize}

